    "narrative": "The Austin Waves lineup is anchored today by **Kyle Tucker** (74.27) and **Drake Baldwin** (71.77), both of whom offer the optimal intersection of high-leverage lineup spots and favorable matchups. **Kyle Tucker** benefits from a strong wind blowing out and a manageable matchup against May, while **Drake Baldwin** earns his elite status through a prime batting order position (#2) and a park factor that significantly inflates his floor. **Josh Lowe** also emerges as a high-upside play (64.99); despite the presence of an elite catcher arm on the opposing side, his dynamic platoon edge against Holmes drives a projection that makes him nearly impossible to bench in a category-dependent format where stolen bases remain the primary scarcity.\n\nThe most difficult decision of the day involved **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.** (53.50), who narrowly missed the starting cut in favor of higher-efficiency options. While his xwOBA profile remains strong, the combination of an elite arm in Ryan and a negative platoon shift pushed his daily efficiency below the threshold established by players like **Sam Antonacci** (60.01) and **Jackson Merrill** (60.19). We are proceeding with **Josh Jung** (56.93) in the utility slot; though his lineup spot is pending, he remains a superior stylistic fit for today\u2019s park factors compared to the bench alternatives.\n\nRisk management remains a priority given the volatility of the slate. We are keeping a close eye on **Coby Mayo** (54.32), who faces a difficult challenge against Fried. While the wind provides a slight +5% boost, the pairing of an elite hold pitcher and a negative platoon dynamic makes him a lower-confidence start. Meanwhile, **Heliot Ramos** (51.70) remains in the lineup as a baseline play, though his lack of a significant platoon advantage against Matz suggests he is the most likely candidate for a mid-game substitution if the game script dictates a need for more defensive stability or a pinch-hitter with a higher ceiling.",
